  "text": "This meta-analysis comprises 70 trials comparing a fluoride toothpaste to placebo or another treatment for preventing dental caries in children and adolescents [CITATION_1] . Studies report the standardized mean difference between treatment and control of tooth areas with carries. Negative values support that the fluoride intervention is beneficial. This data set has some obvious extreme effect sizes and has been used for outlier identification [CITATION_2] Jackson 2008, Gumedze and [CITATION_3] . It has been suggested that there is no evidence of publication bias in the original review though Baker and Jackson argue that this may not be true. Egger's test [CITATION_4] clearly showed that there is evidence for small-study effects (pvalue<0.01 ) and a selection model showed that the correlation between the probability of publication and magnitude of effect is not zero ( ‡ = −0.47 95% ‰Š 5 0.82 to 50.11) suggesting that there is publication bias. This finding complicates the analysis. A forward search analysis had studies 34, 22, 9 and 66 entering in the last four steps and the same studies were found to be outlying if we accounted for small study effects. The same four studies were identified as potential outliers using other outlier identification techniques [CITATION_5] Jackson 2008, Gumedze and [CITATION_6] but it should be noted that in these papers a different numbering of studies is used, we used the one suggested in the original publication). A backward search suggested deleting studies 22, 66, 34 and 21. Figure 6 shows the forward plot of the Cook statistic accompanied by 99% confidence bounds. Three studies (studies 34 ,66 and 22) that enter in thefour last steps of the search seem to have incurred a change that is not explained by chance.",
